pre-emptive right
Homonym Number:
Word Class:noun
Sense Number: 1
Definition:a right of a land purchaser to buy public land on condition that it be improved
Origin:[none]
Register:
Register 2:
Flag: Farm Words
Domain:Rural
Region:[none]
See:
Pronunciation:
Notes:
Citations
Date: 2/1/1841
Source: New Zealand Gazette & Wellington Spectator
Author:
Vol / Page: 2
Edition:
Quote: "Your committee now proceed to state the principles which, in their opinion, should form the basis of a law to be enacted by the Imperial Parliament, for the settlement of the rights of property in New Zealand .. 5. That the holders of lands not in cultivation, whose titles shall have been admitted by the commissioners, shall thereupon have a pre-emptive right of purchase from the crown, at a price not less than 20.s per acre. .."
